ographic and political differences, especially those involving dynamic behaviour such as residential mobility, unemployment duration, job mobility, income inequality, poverty, health and deprivation, national identity, family structure and other aspects of individual's lives as they change over time. This data provides a 'baseline' for policy formulation and for analysing the impact of subsequent differential developments arising out of devolution. The book is also an invaluable resource for establishing pre-existing differences between England and Scotland and evaluating the impact of policy initiatives by the Scottish Executive.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aHousehold surveyszScotland. 0aHouseholdszScotland. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh1 aAlexander, Wendy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBattu, Harminder, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBourque, Nicole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristie, Alex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurtice, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavidson, Carolyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElliott, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErmisch, John F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErmisch, John F., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFindlay, Jeanette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFindlay, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGasteen, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id